6 Publication Bias

6.1 Funnel plot at study level

Figure 3 displays the studiesâ individual effect size estimates aggregated at the study level. The dotted triangle indicates the boundaries for statistical significance on either side of the null effect (i.e., no study-level effect in reality exists; 0).

###############################
# 3M publication bias detection
###############################

# Naturally existing dependence from previous section
Vs = with(dat6, impute_covariance_matrix(v_g2, study, r=.5,
                                        subgroup = sample_id))

# Magnitude of within-study correlations
rho <- 0.5

# Aggregate effects at Study level (level 3)
data_agg_study <- 
  dat6 %>% 
  escalc(data = ., yi = g2, vi = v_g2) %>% 
  aggregate.escalc(cluster = study, rho = rho, weighted = FALSE)

# Contour plot at study level
g <- with(data_agg_study,
     contour_funnel(x = g2, 
                    vi = v_g2, sig = TRUE,
                    xlab = "Study-Level Effect Sizes"))

box()

Figure 3. Contour-Enhanced Funnel Plot of Study-Level Effects 

invisible(NULL)

flextable(g) %>%
  autofit() %>% set_caption("Statistically significant study level effects") %>% fontsize(size = 11, part = "all") %>%
  line_spacing(space = .6, part = "all")

As can be seen, there are 21 effect size estimates aggregated at the study level that are statistically significant in magnitude and positive in direction. This value constitutes ~35% of the total number of study-level aggregate effect sizes in our meta-analysis. Arguably, such evidence does not seem to indicate a tendency for the game-based vocabulary acquisition literature to intentionally favor studies that, as a whole, have found positive and statistically significant effects from game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition. Thus, this form of publication bias at the study-level seems less likely.

6.2 Funnel plot at effect size level

Figure 4 displays the studiesâ individual effect size estimates. As before, the dotted triangle indicates the boundaries for statistical significance on either side of the null effect (i.e., no individual effect in reality exists; 0).

# Contour plot at effect size level
g <- with(dat6,
      contour_funnel(x = g2, 
                     vi = v_g2, sig = TRUE))

box()

Figure 4. Contour-Enhanced Funnel Plot of Individual Effects 

invisible(NULL)

flextable(g) %>%
  autofit() %>% set_caption("Statistically significant individual effects") %>% fontsize(size = 11, part = "all") %>%
  line_spacing(space = .6, part = "all")

As can be seen, there are 60 effect size estimates that are statistically significant in magnitude and positive in direction. This value constitutes ~35.93% percent of the total number of effect sizes in our meta-analysis. On the other hand, there are 13 effect size estimates that are statistically significant in magnitude and negative in direction. This value constitutes ~7.78% percent of the total number of effect sizes in our meta-analysis.

Arguably, the comparison at the effect size level could potentially suggest the possibility of an imbalance in the game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition literature in favor of the positive and statistically significant effects. However, given the lack of such an imbalance at the study-level and presence of multiple positive and statistically significant effects in the less visible literature, the trend seen at the effect size level might indicate a somewhat natural process that is not, for the most part, impacted by the publication industryâs policies as to which studies should be published and which ones should not in the game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition literature.

6.3 Eggerâs test

We also conducted an Eggerâs test (Egger, Smith, Schneider, & Minder, 1997) of funnel plot symmetry. Using this test, we examined the extent to which the standard error (as a measure of precision) of the effect sizes collected from the game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition literature related to the effect sizesâ magnitude. If such a relationship and/or its estimate of intercept, with the latter sometimes referred to as a precision-effect test (PET), rise to statistically significant levels, that could suggest asymmetry (and potentially publication bias) in the funnel plot of effect sizes.

# Eggers test using the same naturally and statistically occurring dependence
ff = rma.mv(g2 ~ SE_egger, V = Vs, 
            random = ~1|study/effect, data = dat6,
            dfs = "contain")

g <- results_rma(ff, drop_rows = 3:7, drop_cols = 9:10, tidy = TRUE)

flextable(dplyr::select(g, -Df)) %>%
  autofit() %>% set_caption("Egger's Test Results") %>% fontsize(size = 11, part = "all") %>%
  line_spacing(space = .6, part = "all")

In our case, given that the p-value for the Eggerâs test for the relationship in question (b = 0.277, p = 0.802; 95% CI[-1.904, 2.458]) and its estimate of intercept (a = 0.391, p = 0.204; 95% CI[-0.218, 1.000]) are both larger than 0.05, we concluded that our funnel plot is sufficiently symmetric and the likelihood of publication bias in the collected sample of game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition studies is small with the caveat that the b estimate has a relatively wide CI.

7 Inter-rater reliability (IRR)

The interrater reliability analysis demonstrated excellent agreement among coders for nearly all categorical moderators. Raw agreement, Fleissâ Îº, and Sâindex values were uniformly high (1.00) for the majority of moderators, with corresponding confidence intervals consistently reaching the upper bound of 1.00. The sole exception was measure, which showed comparatively lower agreement (Raw = 0.571, Îº = 0.375, Sâindex = 0.429) and wider confidence intervals (0.19â0.667), indicating only moderate reliability. Following Norouzian (2021), these findings provide strong evidence that the moderator coding scheme was generally well defined and applied consistently, all disagreements were discussed and resolved.

8 Results of analyses

In this section, we present the results of our analyses in two parts. In the first part, we present the synthesized effects at each time point. As mentioned in the manuscript, results based on a limited number of effects (M) and/or studies (K) should be ignored due to their unreliable nature.

Also presented in the first part is the \(R^2\) test of heterogeneity. \(R^2\) indicates the percentage of change in the total heterogeneity (between- and within the studies) in the true effects of game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition from a model without any MUTOS moderator (a null model) to that from a model that includes a set of MUTOS moderators of interest.

While necessary, the results presented in the first part may not by themselves immediately translate into evidence-based recommendations. This is because the descriptive (synthesized average effects) and the associated inferential results (CIs and p-values) simply denote how much effect at each measurement occasion exists and if that effect is reliably different from 0 at that point in time.

In the second part, we compare the changes that occurred in learnersâ performance from one measurement occasion (baseline) to another (post-test) to specifically measure the potential learning âgainsâ that might have resulted from game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition treatments taking into account the methodological differences that differentiate the studies to varying degrees (see Table 2 in the manuscript for more details on moderators).

Because the second part allows us to measure the gains from game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition across more than one occasion, the results (i.e., synthesized average effects and their associated CIs and p-values) more immediately translate into evidence-based recommendations. To further facilitate such recommendations, in the second part we also measure a minimum expected benefit of using game-based L2 vocabulary acquisition presented in the universal metric of percentages.

8.2 Learning Gains

rs <- results

invisible(lapply(table_names, \(i){

 
  cat(paste0("\n\n### ", i, "\n"))

      
g <- rs[[i]]$ems

# Effects
gains <- if(i=="Time") contrast_rma(g, list("Gain1(Posttest 1 - Baseline)" =c(2,-1))) else contrast_rma(g, brief = TRUE, pretest_name = "Baseline",
                                                                                                        posttest_base_name = "Posttest")


print(kable(dplyr::select(gains$table, -Df),format = "simple", table.attr = "style='width:40%;'",
            caption = paste("Learning gains for", tolower(i))) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "bordered",
                full_width = TRUE, font_size = 9.5))


no <- i != c("Time")

if(no) gain_dif <- contrast_rma(g, gain_dif = TRUE, brief = TRUE, gain_dif_type = "same",
                                pretest_name = "Baseline", posttest_base_name = "Posttest")

if(no) print(kable(dplyr::select(gain_dif$table, -Df),format = "simple", table.attr = "style='width:40%;'",
            caption = paste("Differences in learning gains for", tolower(i))) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "bordered",
                full_width = TRUE, font_size = 9.5))


# Percentages
gain_prob <- prob_rma(gains, gain=TRUE, target_effect=.2)

print(kable(gain_prob,format = "simple", table.attr = "style='width:40%;'",
            caption = paste("Minimum learning gain percentage for", tolower(i))) %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = "bordered",
                full_width = TRUE, font_size = 9.5))
  
}))
